<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Corruption Construction-Contest Article<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.50)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8823'>Jack "Night Wolf" Woolverton</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=8823&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 6, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont">      There is often a flurry of madness in skirmishes as the Free Peoples player is trying to fend off attacks by hordes of Moria Orcs, or pooling all their strength against a massive Cave Troll.  These are several of the ways which people have used to win the game&#8212;numbers and strength, while others just try to get their Free Peoples through site 9.  There is though, another path that may be taken, a path to and through Corruption (burdening the Ring Bearer).  It is a path less traveled (in my experience) and it shall be better explored in this article.  Shall I lead the way?<br>
<br>
     The strategy within this article will come in two sections.  The first will be how to keep your Ring Bearer from being Corrupted, and the second (and most fun) will be a &#8220;how to&#8221; training session.  These will be followed by specific card instructions, just in case you want to skip ahead.  However, this article is not based on building a specific deck, but rather on several ways in which you might travel along this new course of Corruption.<br>
<br>
     There are two main keys to keeping your Ring Bearer safe from the weighty burden of the Ring.  The simplest way is to use common sense.  Do not use the Ring Bearer to fight minions when there are others who can do it for you, even if you want to sacrifice a few burdens in order for other schemes, if you are playing a Corruption deck, it could be fatal.  Use the Ruling Ring instead of Isildur&#8217;s Bane, as a good Corruption deck will be hammering down on the Ring Bearer fairly hard.  The second key is to use cards that will help you remove burdens as much as possible; there are only a few in the Free Peoples cards at the moment that help, but if they are used in the right way, you can be burden free!  Realizing that many decks are not Corruption decks, the second key is the most helpful, as it can be utilized in many Free People strategies.  The first key (about the rings and fighting with the Ring Bearer) is optional, though I find it a good conservative angle when playing other experienced players.<br>
<br>
     As with the Free Peoples strategy, there are two main keys of putting concrete shoes on the Ring Bearer from your Shadow side.  Number one is to use your conditions, events, and special abilities!  Without these, you will have failed to make a Corruption deck.  Well duh, every deck uses those right?! Well&#8230;yes, but my point is that you must use a lot of the specific Corruption cards.  Corruption is a slow business otherwise, and that means the Free Peoples could potentially reach site 9 very fast.  The second key is to use the right cultures (since many conditions and events are culture specific) and minions with heavy strength.  The strength of the minions is a must, as several of the conditions and events require that the minion win a skirmish, or a Free Peoples player exert or take a wound.  For this, I find the Nazgul to be the best minions to play with, but not as most people play them.  The only other point in this paragraph is that if you wish to build a Corruption deck, you cannot use other strategies mixed in with it.  It has to be a straight burdening deck, not a Corruption/Discard deck, etc., it will not work.<br>
<br>
     Now for some of the specific cards; there are many that I could expound upon, but it would take up too much time and space to read, so I am only going to mention several of the most functional card that I have found.<br>
<br>
For the Free Peoples:<br>
<br>
61 Songs of the Blessed Realm-Elven Culture: This card states that whenever you play an Elven tale, you may remove a burden.  There are three different cards in the Elven culture that are tales, and you can have up to 4 of each.  Obviously great for playing Elven decks.  It combines with 35 Council of Elrond-Elven Culture quite well, as The Council allows you to play a tale from your draw deck if you can spot an elf.<br>
<br>
39 Elf-Song-Elven Culture: Spot an Elf to remove a burden.  Once again a great card for the Elven deck.<br>
<br>
74 Gandalf&#8217;s Pipe-Wizard Culture: Must play on Gandalf.  Discard a pipeweed possession and spot X pipes to remove X burdens.  Great when you have a Gandalf or a Shire deck, you will at least get to take one burden off.<br>
<br>
94 Athelas-Gondor Culture: Along with other condition removing cards, this will get rid of any irritating conditions that will not allow healing or burden removing.  A must against Corruption decks if you do not have other condition removing cards.<br>
<br>
312 Sorry About Everything-Shire Culture: Exert a Hobbit to remove a burden.<br>
<br>
Sam and the Gaffer-Sam removes burdens, Gaffer heals him and Frodo.  Rosie Cotton is useful for healing Sam as well.  Plus, the Gaffer&#8217;s Pipe allows tales to be shuffeled back into your draw deck.<br>
<br>
For the Shadow:<br>
<br>
124 Cruel Caradhras-Isengard Culture: Exert an Isengard Minion to make the opponent either exert the Ring Bearer, or add a burden.  Lovely card for fast burdening.<br>
<br>
155 Uruk Spy-Isengard Culture:  Combine with 137 Saruman&#8217;s Reach, thus making the Ring Bearer put on the One Ring, thus exerting your Isengard Minion and discarding a card for each Isengard Minion you can spot in play.  Add a burden for each card discarded this way.  Major Corruption!<br>
<br>
162 Worry-Isengard Culture: Each time an Uruk-Hai wins a skirmish, the opponent must chose to exert the Ring Bearer, or add a burden.<br>
<br>
182 Goblin Spear-Moria Culture: What?!  A spear!  If bearer kills a companion in the skirmish, add 1 burden, or 2 burdens if companion was a Hobbit.  Good card to lay on your Cave Troll (use his hammer in another deck) and other high powered Moria Minions.<br>
<br>
189 Lost to the Goblins-Moria Culture: If Ring Bearer exerts or takes a wound, discard a card from your draw deck for each Moria Minion you spot.  Add a burden for each card discarded in this way.  Limit 3.  Hmm, this might be where big Minions come in handy!<br>
<br>
207 and 209 Black Breath and Blade Tip-Ringwraith Culture: The wounding and iniability to remove wounds and burdens will take the Free Peoples out very fast indeed.  Unless they have atheleas of course.<br>
<br>
211 Drawn to It&#8217;s Power-Ringwraith Culture: Each time a Nazgul kills a companion, add a burden.  Big Minions ride again!  Hint hint&#8230;Witchking and Toldea.<br>
<br>
214 In the Ringwraiths Wake-Ringwraith Culture: If a Nazgul wins a skirmish, Ring Bearer must exert or add a burden.<br>
<br>
228 The Twilight World-Ringwraith Culture: If Ring-Bearer puts on the One Ring, eart a Nazgul to add 2 burdens.  Useful with a Nazgul/Moria Minion Corruption deck.  See above.<br>
<br>
243 Despair-Sauron Culture: If you have 12 Burdens and Companions in the dead pile combined, buh bye Ring Bearer.  Instant Corruption, maybe a new oatmeal?<br>
<br>
252 The Irresistible Shadow-Sauron Culture: 5 burdens and no cards in opponents draw deck?  Buh bye Ring Bearer.  Another oatmeal flavor perhaps?<br>
<br>
244 Desperate Defense of the Ring-Sauron Culture: Plays on a companion, each time companion is assigned to a skirmish, the Free Peoples player must either discard 3 cards from hand, or add a burden.  Works very well against strong companions (Aragorn, Boromirj, Frodo) and with the card&#8230;<br>
<br>
279 Thin and Stretched-Sauron Culture: Plays on the Ring Bearer.  Each time bearer was not assigned to a skirmish, and another companion was, add a burden.  Play this and Desperate Defense on Frodo, and the fun will pile on VERY quickly.  You&#8217;ll be eating oatmeal in no time.<br>
<br>
     If you at least add a few of the burden removing cards into your deck, you should have no problem resisting the weight of the Ring.  The Free Peoples burden removers will work in almost every deck, especially if you are using cards to discard Shadow conditions.  For your Shadow side, remember to make a Corruption deck only, and make sure to put your biggest minions out.  Also keep the balance between the Corruption conditions and events equal to the number of minions, as you will have to exert a minion many times in order to play a card.<br>
<br>
     This strategy has worked very well.  I did not put every detail about Corruption in this article, though I made a valiant effort.  Remember to keep your eyes open for other combinations that you think might work well with the Corruption deck, as there are many different combo&#8217;s that can be played.  I hope that this article has inspired or at least helped you in your understanding of how to Corrupt.  Now you can bring out the best of Sam and Sauron in you, so long for now&#8230;and Thanks for all of you who have read this article!<br>
<br>
Jack &#8220;Night Wolf&#8221; Woolverton<br>
